  "prompt": "Is the act of money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, the act of **money laundering** is **illegal** in virtually every jurisdiction worldwide. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it came from a legal source. This process is used to hide the proceeds of criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or organized crime.\n\n### Why is it illegal?\n1. **Facilitates Crime**: Money laundering enables criminals to profit from illegal activities without detection.\n2. **Undermines Financial Systems**: It compromises the integrity of financial institutions and economies.\n3. **Promotes Corruption**: It often involves bribery and other corrupt practices.\n4. **Tax Evasion**: It deprives governments of tax revenue.\n\n### Legal Consequences\nLaws against money laundering are strict in most countries, and penalties can include:\n- Significant fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Seizure of assets\n- Loss of business licenses\n\nInternational organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to combat money laundering by setting global standards and promoting cooperation among countries.",
